posts.title: Welfare slavery is not a good life and Social Security is not a good retirement. The American dream is to prosper through honest work and invest in your future. The communist dream is to depend on the government to do that for you.
posts.content:
All these "low income" and "social" programs are scams. I just want to keep my money and invest it the way I want. Stop taking portions of my checks and giving it to people who don't work and didn't invest their money. Throughout life we have a lot of time to work, invest, and build wealth. Let us save our money to build our own retirement.

Uncle Sam is not my daddy, I can manage my own money. We need to stop babysitting everybody and let them learn how to be financially responsible. We should teach youth how to invest. Start early. Let people build wealth from a young age. Plant financial seeds so we can all prosper later on.

Personally I advocate for buying stock. Not a crypto guy but I like talking about investing in general, especially when talking to young people. No one taught me how to invest as a kid. I could have retired by now. I don't want to see another generation enter their 30's or 40's with zero investments and zero retirement plans other than social security or a 401k that they don't even monitor.

People who retire on social security are basically still living on welfare at an old age. They're always waiting for that next check. It's just sad and pathetic to see or hear about another person living like a poor welfare bum in their last remaining years. I don't want that to be me, or anyone else. We have to wake up and get involved in our children's future (and our own).

Download a stock app or use whatever trading website you want. Currently I use the Webull app. If you end up not liking the platform you can transfer your shares to another brokerage. Open an account and transfer money into it. Do your research and start learning about a company you can invest in (buy their stock).

Take your time. Find something you believe in and want to support long term. Hopefully the share price (cost of one unit of stock) isn't too high. You want multiple shares. The lower the price, the more shares you can afford to buy. If a stock is too expensive and inflated, it could actually go down in the future. Obviously you want the value of your stock to go up.

Keep paying attention. Be aware of new companies coming out, like Truth Social for example. As you browse the stock market and continue your research, eventually you will find additional companies you like. Start building a small portfolio. Maybe your kids really like one company while mom and dad like another. Don't put all your eggs in one basket (also don't spread yourself too thin). Let your children be involved. Invest for them on your account and prepare them to have their own as soon as they can.

Currently I have 5 different stocks with around 500 shares each. It's a nice round number, not too big or too small. Nothing crazy. Some might consider it low, others might consider it pretty high. When talking about stocks in general, I think a hundred shares of one company is a good goal to start working toward. Consider your retirement. Building wealth takes time. Don't rush it.

By definition, stock is partial ownership. You buy a stake (or many stakes) in the company's future, and as a shareholder you may even get to vote on corporate decisions to help steer the company forward. The more shares you have, the more votes you can cast because you own a higher percentage of the company.

Investing is fun and it creates interesting conversations at work or wherever you go. It feels good to claim something. You become involved with the company and interact with other shareholders around the world. You can get company updates through email or social media. I love supporting my stocks.

I have so much hope for our future together in this land of great opportunity. Stake your claim in America's future and let's all make America great again!!! 🇺🇸
